====Glaucophyta====
{{see also|Cyanobacteria}}

The alga ''[[Cyanophora]]'', a [[glaucophyte]], is thought to be one of the first organisms to contain a chloroplast.<ref name=PlantPhysiology-ChloroplastOrigin /> The glaucophyte chloroplast group is the smallest of the three primary chloroplast lineages, being found in only thirteen species,<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> and is thought to be the one that branched off the earliest.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name=CurrentBiology-Endosymbiosis /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Glaucophytes have chloroplasts which retain a [[peptidoglycan wall]] between their double membranes,<ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" /> like their [[Cyanobacteria#Metabolism and organelles|cyanobacterial]] parent.<ref name=CyanobacterialHeterocysts /> For this reason, glaucophyte chloroplasts are also known as ''[[muroplasts]]''.<ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" /> Glaucophyte chloroplasts also contain [[concentric]] unstacked [[thylakoids]] which surround a [[carboxysome]], an [[icosahedral]] structure that glaucophyte chloroplasts and cyanobacteria keep their [[carbon fixation]] [[enzyme]] [[rubisco]] in. The starch they synthesize collects outside the chloroplast.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Like cyanobacteria, glaucophyte chloroplast thylakoids are studded with light collecting structures called [[phycobilisomes]].<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" /> For these reasons, glaucophyte chloroplasts are considered a primitive intermediate between cyanobacteria and the more evolved chloroplasts in [[red algae]] and [[plants]].<ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" />
{{clear}}
