</div>
}}

The [[chloroplastidan]] chloroplasts, or [[green]] chloroplasts, are another large, highly diverse primary chloroplast lineage. They are commonly known as the [[green algae]] and [[land plants]].<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Green algae">{{cite journal |doi=10.3732/ajb.91.10.1535 |title=Green algae and the origin of land plants |year=2004 |last1=Lewis |first1=L. A. |last2=McCourt |first2=R. M. |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=91 |issue=10 |pages=1535<U+2013>56 |pmid=21652308}}</ref> They differ from glaucophyte and red algal chloroplasts in that they have lost their [[phycobilisomes]], and contain [[chlorophyll b|chlorophyll ''b'']] instead.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Most green chloroplasts are (obviously) [[green]], though some aren't, like some forms of ''[[H<U+00E6>matococcus pluvialis]]'', due to accessory pigments that override the chlorophylls' green colors. Chloroplastidan chloroplasts have lost the [[peptidoglycan wall]] between their double membrane, and have replaced it with an intermembrane space.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Some [[plants]] seem to have kept the [[genes]] for the synthesis of the [[peptidoglycan layer]], though they've been repurposed for use in [[Chloroplast#Chloroplast division|chloroplast division]] instead.<ref name="PNAS<U+2014>Peptidoglycan genes in plants">{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.0510693103 |title=Genes for the peptidoglycan synthesis pathway are essential for chloroplast division in moss |year=2006 |last1=Machida |first1=M. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=103 |issue=17 |pages=6753<U+2013>8 |bibcode=2006PNAS..103.6753M |pmid=16618924 |last2=Takechi |first2=K |last3=Sato |first3=H |last4=Chung |first4=SJ |last5=Kuroiwa |first5=H |last6=Takio |first6=S |last7=Seki |first7=M |last8=Shinozaki |first8=K |last9=Fujita |first9=T |last10=Hasebe |first10=M |last11=Takano |first11=H |pmc=1458953}}</ref>

Most of the chloroplasts depicted in this article are green chloroplasts.

Green algae and plants keep their [[starch]] ''inside'' their chloroplasts,<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Green algae" /> and in plants and some algae, the chloroplast thylakoids are arranged in grana stacks. Some green algal chloroplasts contain a structure called a [[pyrenoid]],<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> which is functionally similar to the glaucophyte [[carboxysome]] in that it's where [[rubisco]] and CO{{sub|2}} are concentrated in the chloroplast.<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Algal pyrenoids">{{cite journal |doi=10.1104/pp.119.1.9 |title=How Do Algae Concentrate CO2 to Increase the Efficiency of Photosynthetic Carbon Fixation? |year=1999 |last1=Moroney |first1=J. V. |journal=Plant Physiology |volume=119 |pages=9<U+2013>16 |pmid=9880340 |last2=Somanchi |first2=A |issue=1 |pmc=1539202}}</ref>

{{plain image|File:Chlamydomonas TEM 07.jpg|[[Transmission electron micrograph]] of ''[[Chlamydomonas reinhardtii]]'', a green alga that contains a pyrenoid surrounded by starch.|300px|left|bottom|triangle|#aaa}}

=====Helicosproidia=====

The [[helicosproidia]] are nonphotosynthetic parasitic green algae that are thought to contain a vestigal chloroplast.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Genes from a chloroplast<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.femsle.2004.02.006 |title=The non-photosynthetic, pathogenic green algaHelicosporidiumsp. Has retained a modified, functional plastid genome |year=2004 |last1=Tartar |first1=Aur<U+00E3><U+00A9>Lien |last2=Boucias |first2=Drion G. |journal=FEMS Microbiology Letters |volume=233 |pages=153<U+2013>7 |pmid=15043882 |issue=1}}</ref> and nuclear genes indicating the presence of a chloroplast have been found in helicosporoidia.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> even if nobody's seen the chloroplast itself.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

===Secondary and tertiary endosymbiosis===

Many other organisms obtained chloroplasts from the primary chloroplast lineages through secondary endosymbiosis<U+2014>engulfing a red or green alga that contained a chloroplast. These chloroplasts are known as secondary plastids.<ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" />

While primary chloroplasts have a double membrane from their [[cyanobacterial]] ancestor, secondary chloroplasts have additional membranes outside of the original two, as a result of the secondary endosymbiotic event, when a nonphotosynthetic [[eukaryote]] engulfed an chloroplast-containing alga but failed to digest it<U+2014>much like the cyanobacterium at the beginning of this story.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> The engulfed alga was broken down, leaving only its chloroplast, and sometimes its [[cell membrane]] and [[Cell nucleus|nucleus]], forming a chloroplast with three to four membranes<ref name="Plant Molecular Biology">{{cite journal|title=Protein import pathways in 'complex' chloroplasts derived from secondary endosymbiosis involving a red algal ancestor|journal=Plant Molecular Biology|year=2005|month=February|pmid=15830125|doi=10.1007/s11103-004-7848-y|volume=57|issue=3|pages=333<U+2013>42|last1=Chaal|first1=Balbir K.|last2=Green|first2=Beverley R.}}</ref><U+2014>the two cyanobacterial membranes, sometimes the eaten alga's cell membrane, and the [[phagosomal vacuole]] from the host's cell membrane.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids />

{{plain image|File:Chloroplast secondary endosymbiosis.svg|Secondary endosymbiosis consisted of a [[eukaryotic]] [[alga]] being engulfed by another eukaryote, forming a chloroplast with three or four membranes.|740px|center|bottom|triangle|#71d7ff}}

{{Plain image with caption|Nucleomorph chloroplast.svg|Diagram of a four membraned chloroplast containing a [[nucleomorph]].|300px|right|bottom|triangle|#13c3a2}}

The genes in the phagocytosed eukaryote's nucleus are often transferred to the secondary host's nucleus.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids />
[[Cryptomonads]] and [[chlorarachniophytes]] retain the phagocytosed eukaryote's nucleus, an object called a [[nucleomorph]],<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> located between the second and third membranes of the chloroplast.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name=PlantPhysiology-ChloroplastOrigin />

All secondary chloroplasts come from [[green algae|green]] and [[red algae]]<U+2014>no secondary chloroplasts from [[glaucophytes]] have been observed, probably because glaucophytes are relatively rare in nature, making them less likely to have been taken up by another eukaryote.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids />

====Green algal derived chloroplasts====

[[Green algae]] have been taken up by the [[euglenids]], [[chlorarachniophytes]], a lineage of [[dinoflagellates]],<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids">{{cite journal |doi=10.1098/rstb.2009.0103 |title=The endosymbiotic origin, diversification and fate of plastids |year=2010 |last1=Keeling |first1=P. J. |journal=Philosophical Transactions of the Royal Society B: Biological Sciences |volume=365 |issue=1541 |pages=729<U+2013>48 |pmid=20124341 |pmc=2817223}}</ref> and possibly the ancestor of the [[chromalveolates]]<ref name="Science<U+2014>Prasinophytes in chromalveolates" /> in three or four separate engulfments.<ref name="MBE<U+2014>Chlorarachniophytes and euglenids">{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/molbev/msl129 |title=The Complete Chloroplast Genome of the Chlorarachniophyte Bigelowiella natans: Evidence for Independent Origins of Chlorarachniophyte and Euglenid Secondary Endosymbionts |year=2006 |last1=Rogers |first1=M. B. |last2=Gilson |first2=P. R. |last3=Su |first3=V. |last4=McFadden |first4=G. I. |last5=Keeling |first5=P. J. |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=24 |pages=54<U+2013>62 |pmid=16990439 |issue=1}}</ref> Many green algal derived chloroplasts contain [[pyrenoids]], but unlike chloroplasts in their green algal ancestors, starch collects in granules outside the chloroplast.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

[[File:Two Euglena.jpg|250px|thumb|''[[Euglena]]'', a [[euglenophyte]], contains secondary chloroplasts from green algae.]]

=====Euglenophytes=====

Euglenophytes are a group of common [[flagellated]] [[protists]] that contain chloroplasts derived from a green alga.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> [[Euglenophyte]] chloroplasts have three membranes<U+2014>it's thought that the membrane of the primary endosymbiont was lost, leaving the cyanobacterial membranes, and the secondary host's phagosomal membrane.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> Euglenophyte chloroplasts have a [[pyrenoid]] and [[thylakoids]] stacked in groups of three. Starch is stored in the form of [[paramylon]], which is contained in membrane-bound granules in the cytoplasm of the euglenophyte.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

[[File:Chlorarachnion reptans.jpg|250px|thumb|left|''[[Chlorarachnion reptans]]'' is a chlorarachniophyte. Chlorarachniophytes replaced their original [[red algal]] endosymbiont with a [[green alga]].]]

=====Chlorarachniophytes=====

[[Chlorarachniophytes]] {{IPAc-en|<U+02CC>|k|l|<U+0254><U+0279>|<U+0259>|<U+02C8>|<U+0279>|<U+00E6>|k|n|i|<U+0275>|<U+02CC>|f|a<U+026A>|t|s}} are a rare group of organisms that also contain chloroplasts derived from green algae,<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> though their story is more complicated than that of the euglenophytes. The ancestor of chlorarachniophytes is thought to have been a [[chromalveolate]], a eukaryote with a ''red'' algal derived chloroplast. It's then thought to have lost its first red algal chloroplast, and later engulfed a green alga, giving it its second, green algal derived chloroplast.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

Chlorarachniophyte chloroplasts are bounded by four membranes, except near the cell membrane, where the chloroplast membranes fuse into a double membrane.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Their thylakoids are arranged in loose stacks of three.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Chlorarachniophytes have a form of starch called [[chrysolaminarin]], which they store in the cytoplasm,<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> often collected around the chloroplast [[pyrenoid]], which bulges into the cytoplasm.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

Chlorarachniophyte chloroplasts are notable because the green alga they are derived from has not been completely broken down<U+2014>its nucleus still persists as a [[nucleomorph]]<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> found between the second and third chloroplast membranes<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><U+2014>the [[periplastid space]], which corresponds to the green alga's cytoplasm.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

=====Early chromalveolates=====

Recent research has suggested that the ancestor of the [[chromalveolates]] acquired a green algal [[prasinophyte]] endosymbiont. The green algal derived chloroplast was lost and replaced with a [[red algal]] derived chloroplast, but not before contributing some of its genes to the early chromalveolate's nucleus. The presence of both green algal and red algal genes in chromalveolates probably helps them thrive under fluctuating light conditions.<ref name="Science<U+2014>Prasinophytes in chromalveolates">{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1172983 |title=Genomic Footprints of a Cryptic Plastid Endosymbiosis in Diatoms |year=2009 |last1=Moustafa |first1=Ahmed |last2=Beszteri |first2=B<U+00E1>nk |last3=Maier |first3=Uwe G. |last4=Bowler |first4=Chris |last5=Valentin |first5=Klaus |last6=Bhattacharya |first6=Debashish |journal=Science |volume=324|issue=5935 |pages=1724<U+2013>6 |pmid=19556510|bibcode = 2009Sci...324.1724M }}</ref>

====Red algal derived chloroplasts <span style="font-weight: 400;">(chromalveolate chloroplasts)</span>====

Like [[green algae]], [[red algae]] have also been taken up in secondary endosymbiosis, though it's thought that all red algal derived chloroplasts are descended from a single red alga that was engulfed by an early [[chromalveolate]], giving rise to the [[chromalveolates]], some of which, like the [[ciliates]], subsequently lost the chloroplast.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><ref name="Biology<U+2014>Campbell & Reece 582<U+2013>592">{{cite book|title=Biology 8th Edition Campbell & Reece|year=2009|publisher=Benjamin Cummings (Pearson)|pages=582<U+2013>92}}</ref> This is still debated though.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><ref name="Biology<U+2014>Campbell & Reece 582<U+2013>592" />

[[Pyrenoids]] and stacked [[thylakoids]] are common in chromalveolate chloroplasts, and the outermost membrane of many are continuous with the [[rough endoplasmic reticulum]] and studded with [[ribosomes]].<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> They have lost their [[phycobilisomes]] and exchanged them for [[chlorophyll c (disambiguation)|chlorophyll ''c'']], which isn't found in primary red algal chloroplasts themselves.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

[[File:Rhodomonas salina CCMP 322.jpg|thumb|''[[Rhodomonas salina]]'' is a [[Cryptomonad|cryptophyte]].]]

=====Cryptophytes=====

[[Cryptomonad|Cryptophytes]], or cryptomonads are a group of algae that contain a red-algal derived chloroplast. Cryptophyte chloroplasts contain a nucleomorph that superficially resembles that of the [[chlorarachniophytes]].<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> Cryptophyte chloroplasts have four membranes, the outermost of which is continuous with the [[rough endoplasmic reticulum]]. They synthesize ordinary [[starch]], which is stored in granules found in the [[periplastid space]]<U+2014>outside the original double membrane, in the place that corresponds to the red alga's cytoplasm. Inside cryptophyte chloroplasts is a [[pyrenoid]] and [[thylakoids]] in stacks of two.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

Their chloroplasts do not have [[phycobilisomes]],<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> but they do have [[phycobilin pigments]] which they keep in their thylakoid space, rather than anchored on the outside of their thylakoid membranes.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name=AJB-historyofplastids />

[[File:Gephyrocapsa oceanica brighter.jpg|thumb|left|[[Scanning electron micrograph]] of ''[[Gephyrocapsa oceanica]]'', a haptophyte.|200px]]

=====Haptophytes=====

[[Haptophytes]] are similar and closely related to cryptophytes, and are thought to be the first chromalveolates to branch off.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Their chloroplasts lack a nucleomorph,<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> their thylakoids are in stacks of three, and they synthesize [[chrysolaminarin]] sugar, which they store completely outside of the chloroplast, in the cytoplasm of the haptophyte.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

=====Heterokontophytes <span style="font-weight: 400;">(stramenopiles)</span>=====
[[File:20110123 185042 Diatom.jpg|thumb|The photosynthetic pigments present in their chloroplasts give [[diatoms]] a greenish-brown color.|250px]]
The [[heterokontophytes]], also known as the stramenopiles, are a very large and diverse group of algae that also contain red algal derived chloroplasts.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Heterokonts include the [[diatoms]] and the [[brown algae]], [[golden algae]],<ref name="Biology<U+2014>Campbell & Reece 582<U+2013>592" /> and [[yellow-green algae]].

Heterokont chloroplasts are very similar to haptophyte chloroplasts, containing a [[pyrenoid]], triplet thylakoids, and with some exceptions,<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> having an [[epiplastid membrane]] connected to the [[endoplasmic reticulum]]. Like haptophytes, heterokontophytes store sugar in [[chrysolaminarin]] granules in the cytoplasm.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> Heterokontophyte chloroplasts contain [[chlorophyll a|chlorophyll ''a'']] and with a few exceptions<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> [[chlorophyll c (disambiguation)|chlorophyll ''c'']],<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> but also have [[carotenoids]] which give them their many colors.<ref name="Biology<U+2014>Campbell & Reece 582<U+2013>592" />

{{Chloroplast cladograms are complicated|width=55%
|caption='''Possible cladogram of chloroplast evolution'''<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name=CurrentBiology-Endosymbiosis /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><br>Circles represent [[endosymbiotic]] events. For clarity, [[dinophyte]] tertiary endosymbioses and many nonphotosynthetic lineages have been omitted.<br><br>
----
{{small|<sup>'''a'''</sup> It is now suspected that [[Chromalveolata]] is [[paraphyletic]] to [[Rhizaria]].<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />}}
}}

=====Apicomplexans=====

[[Apicomplexans]] are another group of chromalveolates. Like the [[helicosproidia]], they're parasitic, and have a nonphotosynthetic chloroplast.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> They were once thought to be related to the helicosproidia, but it is now known that the helicosproida are green algae rather than [[chromalveolates]].<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> The apicomplexans include ''[[Plasmodium]]'', the [[malaria]] parasite. Many apicomplexans keep a [[vestigial]] red algal derived chloroplast<ref name="PLoS<U+2014>Apicomplexans" /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> called an [[apicoplast]], which they inherited from their ancestors. Other apicomplexans like ''[[Cryptosporidium]]'' have lost the chloroplast completely.<ref name="PLoS<U+2014>Apicomplexans" /> Apicomplexans store their energy in [[amylopectin]] starch granules that are located in their cytoplasm, even though they are nonphotosynthetic.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

Apicoplasts have lost all photosynthetic function, and contain no photosynthetic pigments or true thylakoids. They are bounded by four membranes, but the membranes are not connected to the [[endoplasmic reticulum]].<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> The fact that apicomplexans still keep their nonphotosynthetic chloroplast around demonstrates how the chloroplast carries out important functions other than [[photosynthesis]]. [[Plant]] chloroplasts provide plant cells with many important things besides sugar, and apicoplasts are no different<U+2014>they synthesize [[fatty acids]], [[isopentenyl pyrophosphate]], [[iron-sulfur clusters]], and carry out part of the [[heme]] pathway.<ref name="PLoS<U+2014>Apicomplexans" /> This makes the apicoplast an attractive target for drugs to cure apicomplexan-related diseases.<ref name="Wise<U+2014>Plastid diversity" /> The most important apicoplast function is [[isopentenyl pyrophosphate]] synthesis<U+2014>in fact, apicomplexans die when something interferes with this apicoplast function, and when apicomplexans are grown in an isopentenyl pyrophosphate-rich medium, they dump the organelle.<ref name="PLoS<U+2014>Apicomplexans" />

{{clear}}

====Dinophytes====

The [[dinoflagellates]] are yet another very large and diverse group of [[protists]], around half of which are (at least [[mixotrophy|partially]]) [[photosynthetic]].<ref name="Biology<U+2014>Campbell & Reece 582<U+2013>592" /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates">{{cite journal |doi=10.3732/ajb.91.10.1523 |title=Dinoflagellates: A remarkable evolutionary experiment |year=2004 |last1=Hackett |first1=J. D. |last2=Anderson |first2=D. M. |last3=Erdner |first3=D. L. |last4=Bhattacharya |first4=D. |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=91 |issue=10 |pages=1523<U+2013>34 |pmid=21652307}}</ref>

Most dinophyte chloroplasts are secondary [[red algae|red algal]] derived chloroplasts, like other chromalveolate chloroplasts. Many other dinophytes have lost the chloroplast (becoming the nonphotosynthetic kind of dinoflagellate), or replaced it though ''tertiary'' endosymbiosis<ref name=EukaryotCell1>{{cite journal |doi=10.1128/EC.00326-10 |title=Do Red and Green Make Brown?: Perspectives on Plastid Acquisitions within Chromalveolates |year=2011 |last1=Dorrell |first1=R. G. |last2=Smith |first2=A. G. |journal=Eukaryotic Cell |volume=10 |issue=7 |pages=856<U+2013>68 |pmid=21622904 |pmc=3147421}}</ref><U+2014>the engulfment of another [[chromalveolate]] containing a red algal derived chloroplast. Others replaced their original chloroplast with a [[green algae|green algal]] derived one.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" />

Most dinophyte chloroplasts contain at least the [[photosynthetic pigments]] [[chlorophyll a|chlorophyll ''a'']], [[chlorophyll c2|chlorophyll ''c<sub>2</sub>'']], [[beta-carotene|''beta''-carotene]], and at least one dinophyte-unique [[xanthophyll]] ([[peridinin]], [[dinoxanthin]], or [[diadinoxanthin]]), giving many a golden-brown color.<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> All dinophytes store starch in their cytoplasm, and most have chloroplasts with thylakoids arranged in stacks of three.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" />

=====Peridinin-containing dinophyte chloroplast=====
[[File:Ceratium furca.jpg|thumb|300px|''[[Ceratium furca]]'', a [[peridinin]]-containing dinophyte<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1515/botm.1982.25.8.347 |title=Characterization of Peridinin-Chlorophyll <U+03B1>-Proteins from the Marine Dinoflagellate Ceratium furca |year=1982 |last1=Meeson |first1=B. W. |last2=Chang |first2=S. S. |last3=Sweeney |first3=B. M. |journal=Botanica Marina |volume=25 |issue=8 |pages=347<U+2013>50}}</ref>]]

The most common dinophyte chloroplast is the [[peridinin]]-type chloroplast, characterized by the [[carotenoid]] pigment [[peridinin]] in their chloroplasts, along with [[chlorophyll a|chlorophyll ''a'']] and [[chlorophyll c2|chlorophyll ''c''<sub>2</sub>]].<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> Peridinin is not found in any other group of chloroplasts.<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> The peridinin chloroplast is bounded by three membranes (occasionally two),<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> having lost the red algal endosymbiont's original cell membrane.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> The outermost membrane is not connected to the endoplasmic reticulum.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> They contain a [[pyrenoid]], and have triplet-stacked thylakoids. Starch is found outside the chloroplast<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /> An important feature of these chloroplasts is that their [[chloroplast DNA]] is highly [[genome reduction|reduced]] and fragmented into many small circles. Most of the genome has migrated to the nucleus, and only critical photosynthesis-related genes remain in the chloroplast.<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" />

The peridinin chloroplast is thought to be the dinophytes' "original" chloroplast,<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> which has been lost, reduced, replaced, or has company in several other dinophyte lineages.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

=====Fucoxanthin-containing dinophyte chloroplasts <span style="font-weight: 400;">(haptophyte endosymbionts)</span>=====
[[File:Karenia brevis.jpg|200px|thumb|''[[Karenia brevis]]'' is a [[fucoxanthin]]-containing dynophyte responsible for [[algal blooms]] called "[[red tides]]".<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" />]]

The [[fucoxanthin]] dinophyte lineages (including ''[[Karlodinium]]'' and ''[[Karenia (dinoflagellate)|Karenia]]'')<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> lost their original red algal derived chloroplast, and replaced it with a new chloroplast derived from a [[haptophyte]] endosymbiont. ''[[Karlodinium]]'' and ''[[Karenia (dinoflagellate)|Karenia]]'' probably took up different heterokontophytes.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Because the haptophyte chloroplast has four membranes, tertiary endosymbiosis would be expected to create a six membraned chloroplast, adding the haptophyte's [[cell membrane]] and the dinophyte's [[phagosomal vacuole]].<ref name="MBE<U+2014>Fucoxanthin-chloroplasts" /> However, the haptophyte was heavily reduced, stripped of a few membranes and its nucleus, leaving only its chloroplast (with its original double membrane), and possibly one or two additional membranes around it.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /><ref name="MBE<U+2014>Fucoxanthin-chloroplasts">{{cite journal|pmid=10779532|url=http://mbe.oxfordjournals.org/content/17/5/718.full|year=2000|last1=Tengs|first1=T|last2=Dahlberg|first2=OJ|last3=Shalchian-Tabrizi|first3=K|last4=Klaveness|first4=D|last5=Rudi|first5=K|last6=Delwiche|first6=CF|last7=Jakobsen|first7=KS|title=Phylogenetic analyses indicate that the 19'Hexanoyloxy-fucoxanthin-containing dinoflagellates have tertiary plastids of haptophyte origin|volume=17|issue=5|pages=718<U+2013>29|journal=Molecular biology and evolution|doi=10.1093/oxfordjournals.molbev.a026350}}</ref>

Fucoxanthin-containing chloroplasts are characterized by having the pigment [[fucoxanthin]] (actually [[19<U+2032>-hexanoyloxy-fucoxanthin]] and/or [[19<U+2032>-butanoyloxy-fucoxanthin]]) and no peridinin. Fucoxanthin is also found in haptophyte chloroplasts, providing evidence of ancestry.<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" />

[[File:Dinophysis acuminata.jpg|thumb|left|200px|''[[Dinophysis acuminata]]'' has chloroplasts taken from a [[cryptomonad|cryptophyte]].<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids />]]

=====Cryptophyte derived dinophyte chloroplast=====

Members of the genus ''[[Dinophysis]]'' have a [[phycobilin]]-containing<ref name="MBE<U+2014>Fucoxanthin-chloroplasts" /> chloroplast taken from a [[cryptomonad|cryptophyte]].<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> However, the cryptophyte is not an endosymbiont<U+2014>only the chloroplast seems to have been taken, and the chloroplast has been stripped of its [[nucleomorph]] and outermost two membranes, leaving just a two-membraned chloroplast. Cryptophyte chloroplasts require their nucleomorph to maintain themselves, and ''Dinophysis'' species grown in [[cell culture]] alone cannot survive, so it's possible (but not confirmed) that the ''Dinophysis'' chloroplast is a [[kleptoplast]]<U+2014>if so, ''Dinophysis'' chloroplasts wear out and ''Dinophysis'' species must continually engulf cryptophytes to obtain new chloroplasts to replace the old ones.<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" />

=====Diatom derived dinophyte chloroplasts=====

Some dinophytes, like ''[[Kryptoperidinium]]'' and ''[[Durinskia]]''<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> have a [[diatom]] ([[heterokontophyte]]) derived chloroplast.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> These chloroplasts are bounded by up to ''five'' membranes,<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /> (depending on whether you count the entire diatom endosymbiont as the chloroplast, or just the red algal derived chloroplast inside it). The diatom endosymbiont has been reduced relatively little<U+2014>it still retains its original [[mitochondria]],<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> and has [[endoplasmic reticulum]], [[ribosomes]], a [[cell nucleus|nucleus]], and of course, red algal derived chloroplasts<U+2014>practically a complete [[cell (biology)|cell]],<ref name="Grana<U+2014>Dinophyte chloroplasts">{{cite journal |doi=10.1080/00173139908559217 |title=Dinophyte chloroplasts and phylogeny - A review |year=1999 |last1=Schnepf |first1=Eberhard |last2=Elbr<U+00E4>chter |first2=Malte |journal=Grana |volume=38 |issue=2<U+2013>3 |pages=81<U+2013>97}}</ref> all inside the host's [[endoplasmic reticulum lumen]].<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> However the diatom endosymbiont can't store its own food<U+2014>its starch is found in granules in the dinophyte host's cytoplasm instead.<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="Grana<U+2014>Dinophyte chloroplasts" /> The diatom endosymbiont's nucleus is present, but it probably can't be called a [[nucleomorph]] because it shows no sign of [[genome reduction]], and might have even been ''expanded''.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" /> Diatoms have been engulfed by dinoflagellates at least three times.<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

The diatom endosymbiont is bounded by a single membrane,<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> inside it are chloroplasts with four membranes. Like the diatom endosymbiont's diatom ancestor, the chloroplasts have triplet thylakoids and [[pyrenoids]].<ref name="Grana<U+2014>Dinophyte chloroplasts" />

In some of these [[genera]], the diatom endosymbiont's chloroplasts aren't the only chloroplasts in the dinophyte. The original three-membraned peridinin chloroplast is still around, converted to an [[Eyespot apparatus|eyespot]].<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids /><ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

=====Prasinophyte <span style="font-weight: 400;">(green algal)</span> derived dinophyte chloroplast=====

''[[Lepidodinium viride]]'' and its close relatives are dinophytes that lost their original peridinin chloroplast and replaced it with a green algal derived chloroplast (more specifically, a [[prasinophyte]]).<ref name="Springer<U+2014>The Chloroplast<U+2014>Chloroplast shapes" /><ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> ''[[Lepidodinium]]'' is the only dinophyte that has a chloroplast that's not from the [[rhodoplast]] lineage. The chloroplast is surrounded by two membranes and has no nucleomorph<U+2014>all the nucleomorph genes have been transferred to the dinophyte [[cell nucleus|nucleus]].<ref name="AJB<U+2014>Dinoflagellates" /> The endosymbiotic event that led to this chloroplast was [[serial secondary endosymbiosis]] rather than tertiary endosymbiosis<U+2014>the endosymbiont was a [[green alga]] containing a primary chloroplast (making a secondary chloroplast).<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

===Chromatophores===
While most chloroplasts originate from that first set of endosymbiotic events, ''[[Paulinella]] chromatophora'' is an exception, which has acquired a photosynthetic cyanobacterial endosymbiont more recently. It is not closely related to chloroplasts of other eukaryotes.<ref name=AJB-historyofplastids/> Being in the early stages of endosymbiosis, Paulinella chromatophora can offer some insights into how chloroplasts evolved.<ref name="BMCBiology-EvolvinganOrganelle">{{cite journal |doi=10.1186/1741-7007-10-35 |title=Evolving a photosynthetic organelle |year=2012 |last1=Nakayama |first1=Takuro |last2=Archibald |first2=John M |journal=BMC Biology |volume=10 |pages=35 |pmid=22531210 |pmc=3337241}}</ref><ref name=MolecularBiologyEvol-EndosymbioticGeneTransfer>{{cite journal |doi=10.1093/molbev/msq209 |title=Endosymbiotic Gene Transfer and Transcriptional Regulation of Transferred Genes in Paulinella chromatophora |year=2010 |last1=Nowack |first1=E. C. M. |last2=Vogel |first2=H. |last3=Groth |first3=M. |last4=Grossman |first4=A. R. |last5=Melkonian |first5=M. |last6=Gl<U+00F6>ckner |first6=G. |journal=Molecular Biology and Evolution |volume=28 |pages=407<U+2013>22 |pmid=20702568 |issue=1}}</ref> ''Paulinella'' cells contain one or two sausage shaped blue-green photosynthesizing structures called [[chromatophores]],<ref name=BMCBiology-EvolvinganOrganelle /><ref name=MolecularBiologyEvol-EndosymbioticGeneTransfer /> descended from the cyanobacterium ''[[Synechococcus]]''. Chromatophores cannot survive outside their host.<ref name=BMCBiology-EvolvinganOrganelle /> Chromatophore DNA is about a million [[base pairs]] long, containing around 850 protein encoding [[genes]]<U+2014>far less than the three million base pair ''Synechococcus'' genome,<ref name=BMCBiology-EvolvinganOrganelle /> but much larger than the ~150,000 base pair genome of the more assimilated chloroplast.<ref name=BioscienceExplained /><ref name=PNAS-RatesofctDNAevolution /><ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany /> Chromatophores have transferred much less of their DNA to the nucleus of their host. About 0.3<U+2013>0.8% of the nuclear DNA in ''Paulinella'' is from the chromatophore, compared with 11<U+2013>14% from the chloroplast in plants.<ref name=MolecularBiologyEvol-EndosymbioticGeneTransfer />

===Kleptoplastidy===

In some groups of [[mixotrophic]] [[protist]]s, like some [[dinoflagellate]]s, chloroplasts are separated from a captured alga or [[diatom]] and used temporarily. These [[kleptoplasty|klepto chloroplasts]] may only have a lifetime of a few days and are then replaced.<ref name=Skovgaard>{{cite journal |doi=10.3354/ame015293 |title=Role of chloroplast retention in a marine dinoflagellate |year=1998 |last1=Skovgaard |first1=Alf |journal=Aquatic Microbial Ecology |volume=15 |pages=293<U+2013>301}}</ref>

==Chloroplast DNA==
{{Split2|Chloroplast DNA|date=July 2013}}
{{See also|List of sequenced plastomes}}

Chloroplasts have their own [[DNA]],<ref>C.Michael Hogan. 2010. [http://www.eoearth.org/articles/view/158858/?topic=49496 ''Deoxyribonucleic acid''. Encyclopedia of Earth. National Council for Science and the Environment.] eds. S.Draggan and C.Cleveland. Washington DC</ref> often abbreviated as '''ctDNA''',<ref>{{cite web|title=ctDNA&nbsp;<U+2014> chloroplast DNA|url=http://www.all-acronyms.com/cat/7/CTDNA/chloroplast_DNA/854720|publisher=AllAcronyms.com|accessdate=2 January 2013}}</ref> or '''cpDNA'''.<ref>{{cite book|title=The Oxford Dictionary of Abbreviations|year=1998|location=ctDNA<U+2014>Dictionary definition|url=http://www.encyclopedia.com/doc/1O25-ctDNA.html}}</ref> It is also known as the [[plastome]]. Its existence was first proved in 1962,<ref name=BioscienceExplained>{{cite book|last=Dann|first=Leighton|title=Bioscience<U+2014>Explained|year=2002|publisher=BIOSCIENCE EXPLAINED|location=Green DNA|url=http://www.bioscience-explained.org/ENvol1_2/pdf/ctDNAEN.pdf}}</ref> and first sequenced in 1986<U+2014>when two Japanese research teams sequenced the chloroplast DNA of [[liverwort]] and [[tobacco plant|tobacco]].<ref name="Chloroplasts and Other Plastids">{{cite web|title=Chloroplasts and Other Plastids|url=http://www.biologie.uni-hamburg.de/b-online/e23/23a.htm|publisher=University of Hamburg|accessdate=27 December 2012}}</ref> Since then, hundreds of chloroplast DNAs from various species have been [[DNA sequencing|sequenced]], but they're mostly those of [[land plants]] and [[green algae]]<U+2014>[[glaucophytes]], [[red algae]], and other algal groups are extremely underrepresented, potentially introducing some [[Selection bias|bias]] in views of "typical" chloroplast DNA structure and content.<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18>{{cite book |last=Sandelius |first=Anna Stina |title=The Chloroplast: Interactions with the Environment |year=2009 |publisher=Springer |isbn=978-3-540-68696-5 |page=18 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=aQR__H2XBnUC&pg=PA18}}</ref>

===Molecular structure===
{{Chloroplast DNA|caption='''Chloroplast DNA''' Interactive gene map of chloroplast DNA from ''[[Nicotiana tabacum]]''. Segments with labels on the inside reside on the B strand of [[DNA]], segments with labels on the outside are on the A strand. Notches indicate [[introns]].}}

Chloroplast DNAs are [[circular DNA|circular]], and are typically 120,000<U+2013>170,000 [[base pairs]] long.<ref name=BioscienceExplained /><ref name=PNAS-RatesofctDNAevolution /><ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany /> They can have a contour length of around 30<U+2013>60 micrometers, and have a mass of about 80<U+2013>130 million [[dalton (unit)|dalton]]s.<ref name=IntroductiontoPlantCellDevelopment-ctDNA-62>{{cite book |last=Burgess |first=Jeremy |title=An introduction to plant cell development |year=1989 |publisher=Cambridge university press |location=Cambridge |isbn=0-521-31611-1 |page=62 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=r808AAAAIAAJ&pg=PA62}}</ref>

Most chloroplasts have their entire chloroplast genome combined into a single large ring, though those of [[dinophyte algae]] are a notable exception<U+2014>their genome is broken up into about forty small [[plasmids]], each 2,000<U+2013>10,000 [[base pairs]] long.<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> Each minicircle contains one to three genes,<ref name=PlantPhysiology-ChloroplastOrigin /><ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> but blank plasmids, with no coding DNA, have also been found.

====Inverted repeats====
Many chloroplast DNAs contain two ''inverted repeats'', which separate a long single copy section (LSC) from a short single copy section (SSC).<ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany>{{cite journal |doi=10.3732/ajb.94.3.275 |title=Comparison of whole chloroplast genome sequences to choose noncoding regions for phylogenetic studies in angiosperms: The tortoise and the hare III |year=2007 |last1=Shaw |first1=J. |last2=Lickey |first2=E. B. |last3=Schilling |first3=E. E. |last4=Small |first4=R. L. |journal=American Journal of Botany |volume=94 |issue=3 |pages=275<U+2013>88 |pmid=21636401}}</ref>

The inverted repeats vary wildly in length, ranging from 4,000 to 25,000 [[base pairs]] long each.<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> Inverted repeats in plants tend to be at the upper end of this range, each being 20,000<U+2013>25,000 base pairs long.<ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany /><ref name=PNAS-InvertedRepeats>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.76.1.41 |title=Inverted Repeats in Chloroplast DNA from Higher Plants |year=1979 |last1=Kolodner |first1=R. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=76 |pages=41<U+2013>5 |pmid=16592612 |last2=Tewari |first2=KK |issue=1 |pmc=382872|bibcode = 1979PNAS...76...41K }}</ref>
The inverted repeat regions usually contain three [[ribosomal RNA]] and two [[tRNA]] genes, but they can be expanded or [[genome reduction|reduced]] to contain as few as four or as many as over 150 genes.<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 />
While a given pair of inverted repeats are rarely completely identical, they are always very similar to each other, apparently resulting from [[concerted evolution]].<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 />

The inverted repeat regions are highly [[Conserved sequence|conserved]] among land plants, and accumulate few mutations.<ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany /><ref name=PNAS-InvertedRepeats /> Similar inverted repeats exist in the genomes of cyanobacteria and the other two chloroplast lineages ([[glaucophyta]] and [[rhodophyce<U+00E6>]]), suggesting that they predate the chloroplast,<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> though some chloroplast DNAs like those of [[peas]] and a few [[red algae]]<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> have since lost the inverted repeats.<ref name=PNAS-InvertedRepeats /><ref name=Cell-ctDNArearrangement /> Others, like the red alga ''[[Porphyra]]'' flipped one of its inverted repeats (making them direct repeats).<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 /> It is possible that the inverted repeats help stabilize the rest of the chloroplast genome, as chloroplast DNAs which have lost some of the inverted repeat segments tend to get rearranged more.<ref name=Cell-ctDNArearrangement>{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/0092-8674(82)90170-2 |title=Chloroplast DNA rearrangements are more frequent when a large inverted repeat sequence is lost |year=1982 |last1=Palmer |first1=Jeffrey D. |last2=Thompson |first2=William F. |journal=Cell |volume=29 |issue=2 |pages=537<U+2013>50 |pmid=6288261}}</ref>

====Linear structure====

Chloroplast DNAs have long been thought to have a [[circular genome|circular structure]], but some evidence suggests that chloroplast DNA more commonly takes a [[linear]] shape.<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>Linear chloroplast DNA">{{cite journal |doi=10.1105/tpc.160771 |title=Circular Chloroplast Chromosomes: The Grand Illusion |year=2004 |last1=Bendich |first1=A. J. |journal=The Plant Cell Online |volume=16 |issue=7 |pages=1661<U+2013>6 |pmid=15235123 |pmc=514151}}</ref> Over 95% of the chloroplast DNA in [[corn]] chloroplasts has been observed to be in branched linear form rather than individual circles.<ref name=Springer-TheChloroplast-18 />

====Nucleoids====

New chloroplasts may contain up to 100 copies of their DNA,<ref name=BioscienceExplained /> though the number of chloroplast DNA copies decreases to about 15<U+2013>20 as the chloroplasts age.<ref name=PlantBiochemistry>{{cite book|title=Plant Biochemistry |edition=3rd |year=2005|publisher=Academic Press|page=517|url=http://books.google.com/?id=qHCzrDHajtoC&pg=PA517&lpg=PA517&dq=number+of+copies+of+ctDNA+per+chloroplast#v=onepage&q=number%20of%20copies%20of%20ctDNA%20per%20chloroplast&f=false|isbn=9780120883912}}</ref> They are usually packed into [[nucleoids]] which can contain several identical chloroplast DNA rings. Many nucleoids can be found in each chloroplast.<ref name=IntroductiontoPlantCellDevelopment-ctDNA-62 />

Though chloroplast DNA is not associated with true [[histones]],<ref name=Biology-Campbell&Reece /> in [[red algae]], a histone-like chloroplast protein (HC) coded by the chloroplast DNA that tightly packs each chloroplast DNA ring into a [[nucleoid]] has been found.<ref name="TPC-ChloroplastNucleoids">{{cite journal |doi=10.1105/tpc.002717 |title=Detection and Localization of a Chloroplast-Encoded HU-Like Protein That Organizes Chloroplast Nucleoids |year=2002 |last1=Kobayashi |first1=T. |journal=The Plant Cell Online |volume=14 |issue=7 |pages=1579<U+2013>89 |pmid=12119376 |last2=Takahara |first2=M |last3=Miyagishima |first3=SY |last4=Kuroiwa |first4=H |last5=Sasaki |first5=N |last6=Ohta |first6=N |last7=Matsuzaki |first7=M |last8=Kuroiwa |first8=T |pmc=150708}}</ref>

In primitive [[red algae]], the chloroplast DNA nucleoids are clustered in the center of the chloroplast, while in green plants and [[green algae]], the nucleoids are dispersed throughout the [[stroma (fluid)|stroma]].<ref name="TPC-ChloroplastNucleoids" />

===DNA replication===
{{empty section|date=August 2013}}

===Gene content and protein synthesis===

The chloroplast genome most commonly includes around 100 genes<ref name="PlantPhysiology-ChloroplastOrigin">{{cite journal |doi=10.1104/pp.125.1.50 |title=Chloroplast Origin and Integration |year=2001 |last1=McFadden |first1=G. I. |journal=Plant Physiology |volume=125 |pages=50<U+2013>3 |pmid=11154294 |issue=1 |pmc=1539323}}</ref><ref name=PNAS-RatesofctDNAevolution>{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.91.15.6795 |title=Rates and Patterns of Chloroplast DNA Evolution |year=1994 |last1=Clegg |first1=M. T. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=91 |issue=15 |pages=6795<U+2013>801 |pmid=8041699 |last2=Gaut |first2=BS |last3=Learn Jr |first3=GH |last4=Morton |first4=BR |pmc=44285|bibcode = 1994PNAS...91.6795C }}</ref> which code for a variety of things, mostly to do with the [[protein synthesis|protein pipeline]] and [[photosynthesis]]. As in [[prokaryotes]], genes in chloroplast DNA are organized into [[operons]].<ref name=PlantPhysiology-ChloroplastOrigin />

Among land plants, the contents of the chloroplast genome are fairly similar<ref name=AmericanJournalofBotany /><U+2014>they code for four [[ribosomal RNAs]], 30<U+2013>31 [[tRNAs]], 21 [[ribosomal proteins]], and four [[RNA polymerase]] subunits,<ref name=ASM-ChloroplastRibosomesandProteinSynthesis /><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1023/A:1007564209282 |year=1998 |last1=Wakasugi |first1=T. |last2=Sugita |first2=M. |last3=Tsudzuki |first3=T. |last4=Sugiura |first4=M. |journal=Plant Molecular Biology Reporter |volume=16 |issue=3 |pages=231<U+2013>41 |title=Updated gene map of tobacco chloroplast DNA}}</ref> involved in protein synthesis. For photosynthesis, the chloroplast DNA includes genes for 28 [[thylakoid]] proteins and the large [[Rubisco]] subunit.<ref name=ASM-ChloroplastRibosomesandProteinSynthesis /> In addition, its genes encode eleven subunits of a protein complex which mediates [[redox]] reactions to recycle electrons,<ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1007/s00294-008-0208-8 |title=From chloroplasts to "cryptic" plastids: Evolution of plastid genomes in parasitic plants |year=2008 |last1=Krause |first1=Kirsten |journal=Current Genetics |volume=54 |issue=3 |pages=111<U+2013>21 |pmid=18696071}}</ref> which is similar to the [[NADH dehydrogenase (ubiquinone)|NADH dehydrogenase]] found in mitochondria.<ref name=ASM-ChloroplastRibosomesandProteinSynthesis /><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1105/tpc.111.090597 |title=Multistep Assembly of Chloroplast NADH Dehydrogenase-Like Subcomplex a Requires Several Nucleus-Encoded Proteins, Including CRR41 and CRR42, in Arabidopsis |year=2012 |last1=Peng |first1=L. |last2=Fukao |first2=Y. |last3=Fujiwara |first3=M. |last4=Shikanai |first4=T. |journal=The Plant Cell |volume=24 |pages=202<U+2013>14 |pmid=22274627 |issue=1 |pmc=3289569}}</ref>

====Chloroplast genome reduction and gene transfer====

Over time, many parts of the chloroplast genome were transferred to the [[nuclear genome]] of the host,<ref name=BioscienceExplained /><ref name=PNAS-RatesofctDNAevolution /><ref>{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nature01435 |title=Direct measurement of the transfer rate of chloroplast DNA into the nucleus |year=2003 |last1=Huang |first1=Chun Y. |last2=Ayliffe |first2=Michael A. |last3=Timmis |first3=Jeremy N. |journal=Nature |volume=422 |issue=6927 |pages=72<U+2013>6 |pmid=12594458|bibcode = 2003Natur.422...72H }}</ref> a process called ''[[endosymbiotic gene transfer]]''.
As a result, the chloroplast genome is heavily [[genome reduction|reduced]] compared to that of free-living cyanobacteria. Chloroplasts may contain 60<U+2013>100 genes whereas cyanobacteria often have more than 1500 genes in their genome.<ref name="PNAS<U+2014>Cyanobacterial genes in Arabidopsis">{{cite journal |doi=10.1073/pnas.182432999 |title=Evolutionary analysis of Arabidopsis, cyanobacterial, and chloroplast genomes reveals plastid phylogeny and thousands of cyanobacterial genes in the nucleus |year=2002 |last1=Martin |first1=W. |journal=Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences |volume=99 |issue=19 |pages=12246<U+2013>51 |bibcode=2002PNAS...9912246M |pmid=12218172 |last2=Rujan |first2=T |last3=Richly |first3=E |last4=Hansen |first4=A |last5=Cornelsen |first5=S |last6=Lins |first6=T |last7=Leister |first7=D |last8=Stoebe |first8=B |last9=Hasegawa |first9=M |last10=Penny |first10=D |pmc=129430}}</ref>

Endosymbiotic gene transfer is how we know about the [[Chloroplast#Secondary and tertiary endosymbiosis|lost chloroplasts]] in many [[chromalveolate]] lineages. Even if a chloroplast is eventually lost, the genes it donated to the former host's nucleus persist, providing evidence for the lost chloroplast's existence. For example, while [[diatoms]] (a [[heterokontophyte]]) now have a [[red algal derived chloroplast]], the presence of many [[green algal]] genes in the diatom nucleus provide evidence that the diatom ancestor (probably the ancestor of all chromalveolates too) had a [[green algal derived chloroplast]] at some point, which was subsequently replaced by the red chloroplast.<ref name="Science<U+2014>Prasinophytes in chromalveolates" />

In land plants, some 11<U+2013>14% of the DNA in their nuclei can be traced back to the chloroplast,<ref name=MolecularBiologyEvol-EndosymbioticGeneTransfer /> up to 18% in ''[[Arabidopsis]]'', corresponding to about 4,500 protein-coding genes.<ref name="Current Biology<U+2014>Algal genomics">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/j.cub.2006.11.008 |title=Algal Genomics: Exploring the Imprint of Endosymbiosis |year=2006 |last1=Archibald |first1=John M. |journal=Current Biology |volume=16 |issue=24 |pages=R1033<U+2013>5 |pmid=17174910}}</ref> There have been a few recent transfers of genes from the chloroplast DNA to the nuclear genome in land plants.<ref name=PNAS-RatesofctDNAevolution />

Of the approximately three-thousand proteins found in chloroplasts, some 95% of them are encoded by nuclear genes. Many of the chloroplast's protein complexes consist of subunits from both the chloroplast genome and the host's nuclear genome. As a result, [[protein synthesis]] must be coordinated between the chloroplast and the nucleus. The chloroplast is mostly under nuclear control, though chloroplasts can also give out signals regulating [[gene expression]] in the nucleus, called ''[[retrograde signaling (cell biology)|retrograde signaling]]''.<ref name=Science-ChloroplastSignals-NuclearGeneExpression>{{cite journal |bibcode=2007Sci...316..715K |title=Signals from Chloroplasts Converge to Regulate Nuclear Gene Expression |last1=Koussevitzky |first1=Shai |last2=Nott |first2=A |first3=TC |first4=F |first5=G |first6=M |first7=J |first8=R |first9=J  |volume=316 |year=2007 |pages=715<U+2013>9 |journal=Science |doi=10.1126/science.1140516 |pmid=17395793 |issue=5825 |last3=Mockler |last4=Hong |last5=Sachetto-Martins |last6=Surpin |last7=Lim |last8=Mittler |last9=Chory |doi_brokendate=August 24, 2013 |url=http://www.sciencemag.org/content/316/5825/715.short}}</ref>

====Protein synthesis====
{{See also|transcription (genetics)|Translation (biology)|label 1=Transcription|label 2=translation}}
Protein synthesis within chloroplasts relies on an [[RNA polymerase]] coded by the chloroplast's own genome, which is related to RNA polymerases found in bacteria. Chloroplasts also contain a mysterious second RNA polymerase that is encoded by the plant's nuclear genome. The two RNA polymerases may recognize and bind to different kinds of [[promoter (genetics)|promoters]] within the chloroplast genome.<ref name=Science-ChloroplastRNAPolymerases>{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.277.5327.809 |title=Mitochondrial and Chloroplast Phage-Type RNA Polymerases in Arabidopsis |year=1997 |last1=Hedtke |first1=B. |journal=Science |volume=277 |issue=5327 |pages=809<U+2013>11 |pmid=9242608 |last2=B<U+00F6>rner |first2=T |last3=Weihe |first3=A}}</ref> The [[ribosomes]] in chloroplasts are similar to bacterial ribosomes.<ref name=ASM-ChloroplastRibosomesandProteinSynthesis>{{cite journal |pmid=7854253 |pmc=372988 |year=1994 |last1=Harris |first1=EH |last2=Boynton |first2=JE |last3=Gillham |first3=NW |title=Chloroplast ribosomes and protein synthesis |volume=58 |issue=4 |pages=700<U+2013>54 |journal=Microbiological reviews}}</ref>

{{Expand section|Genome size differences between algae and land plants, chloroplast stuff coded by the nucleus, DNA replication, NADPH redox, special tRNA synthetases, etc.|date=January 2013}}

===Protein targeting and import===
{{See also|Translation (biology)|label 1=Translation}}

The movement of so many chloroplast genes to the nucleus means that lots of chloroplast [[proteins]] that were supposed to be [[Translation (biology)|translated]] in the chloroplast are now synthesized in the cytoplasm. This means that these proteins must be directed back to the chloroplast, and imported through at least two chloroplast membranes.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nrm1333 |title=Plant cell biology: Protein import into chloroplasts |year=2004 |last1=Soll |first1=J<U+00FC>rgen |last2=Schleiff |first2=Enrico |journal=Nature Reviews Molecular Cell Biology |volume=5 |issue=3 |pages=198<U+2013>208 |pmid=14991000}}</ref>

Curiously, around half of the protein products of transferred genes aren't even targeted back to the chloroplast. Many became [[exaptations]], taking on new functions like participating in [[cell division]], [[protein routing]], and even [[disease resistance]]. A few chloroplast genes found new homes in the [[mitochondrial genome]]<U+2014>most became nonfunctional [[pseudogenes]], though a few [[tRNA]] genes still work in the [[mitochondrion]].<ref name="PNAS<U+2014>Cyanobacterial genes in Arabidopsis" /> Some transferred chloroplast DNA protein products get directed to the [[secretory pathway]]<ref name="PNAS<U+2014>Cyanobacterial genes in Arabidopsis" /> (though it should be noted that many [[secondary plastids]] are bounded by an outermost membrane derived from the host's [[cell membrane]], and therefore [[topologically]] outside of the cell, because to reach the chloroplast from the [[cytosol]], you have to cross the [[cell membrane]], just like if you were headed for the [[extracellular space]]. In those cases, chloroplast-targeted proteins do initially travel along the secretory pathway).<ref name="RSTB<U+2014>Endosymbiosis of plastids" />

Because the cell acquiring a chloroplast [[Chloroplast#Primary endosymbiosis|already]] had [[mitochondria]] (and [[peroxisomes]], and a [[cell membrane]] for secretion), the new chloroplast host had to develop a unique [[protein targeting system]] to avoid having chloroplast proteins being sent to the wrong [[organelle]], and the wrong proteins being sent to the chloroplast.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

====Cytoplasmic translation and N-terminal transit sequences====
{{See also|Polypeptide|protein|translation (biology)|label 3=translation}}

{{plain image|File:Tetrapeptide structural formulae.svg|A [[polypeptide]] with four [[amino acids]] linked together. At the left is the [[N-terminus]], with its [[amino group|amino]] (H<sub>2</sub>'''N''') group in green. The blue [[C-terminus]], with its [[carboxyl group]] ('''C'''O<sub>2</sub>H) is at the right.|350px|right|bottom|triangle|#00aa15}}

[[Polypeptides]], the precursors of [[proteins]], are chains of [[amino acids]]. The two ends of a polypeptide are called the [[N-terminus]], or ''amino end'', and the [[C-terminus]], or ''carboxyl end''.<ref name="Biology 8th edition<U+2014>Campbell & Reece<U+2014>340">{{cite book|title=Biology 8th edition<U+2014>Campbell & Reece|year=2008|publisher=Benjamin Cummings|isbn=978-0-321-54325-7|page=340}}</ref> For many (but not all)<ref name="Structure and Function of Plastids<U+2014>Protein import">{{cite book |last=Wise |first=Robert R. |title=Structure and function of plastids |year=2007 |publisher=Springer |location=Berlin |isbn=978-1-4020-6570-5 |pages=53<U+2013>74 |url=http://books.google.com/books?id=FKeCVPbJ3asC&pg=PA59 |last2=Hoober |first2=J. Kenneth}}</ref> chloroplast proteins encoded by [[cell nucleus|nuclear]] genes, ''[[cleavable transit peptides]]'' are added to the N-termini of the polypeptides, which are used to help direct the polypeptide to the chloroplast for import<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Motifs in Rubisco transit peptides">{{cite journal |doi=10.1104/pp.105.074575 |title=Functional Characterization of Sequence Motifs in the Transit Peptide of Arabidopsis Small Subunit of Rubisco |year=2006 |last1=Lee |first1=D. W. |journal=Plant Physiology |volume=140 |issue=2 |pages=466<U+2013>83 |pmid=16384899 |last2=Lee |first2=S |last3=Lee |first3=GJ |last4=Lee |first4=KH |last5=Kim |first5=S |last6=Cheong |first6=GW |last7=Hwang |first7=I |pmc=1361317}}</ref> (N-terminal transit peptides are also used to direct polypeptides to plant [[mitochondria]]).<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>14-3-3 proteins" />
N-terminal transit sequences are also called ''presequences''<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> because they are located at the "front" end of a polypeptide<U+2014>[[ribosomes]] synthesize polypeptides from the N-terminus to the C-terminus.<ref name="Biology 8th edition<U+2014>Campbell & Reece<U+2014>340" />

Chloroplast transit peptides exhibit huge variation in length and [[amino acid sequence]].<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Motifs in Rubisco transit peptides" /> They can be from 20<U+2013>150 amino acids long<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><U+2014>an unusually long length, suggesting that transit peptides are actually collections of [[protein domain|domains]] with different functions.<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Motifs in Rubisco transit peptides" /> Transit peptides tend to be [[positively charged]],<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> rich in [[hydroxyl group|hydroxylated]] amino acids such as [[serine]], [[threonine]], and [[proline]], and poor in [[acidic]] amino acids like [[aspartic acid]] and [[glutamic acid]].<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Motifs in Rubisco transit peptides" /> In an [[aqueous solution]], the transit sequence forms a random coil.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Not all chloroplast proteins include a N-terminal cleavable transit peptide though.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> Some include the transit sequence within the [[mature protein|functional part]] of the protein itself.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> A few have their transit sequence appended to their [[C-terminus]] instead.<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>C-terminal transit sequences">{{cite journal |doi=10.1105/tpc.112.096248 |title=A Transit Peptide-Like Sorting Signal at the C Terminus Directs the Bienertia sinuspersici Preprotein Receptor Toc159 to the Chloroplast Outer Membrane |year=2012 |last1=Lung |first1=S.-C. |last2=Chuong |first2=S. D. X. |journal=The Plant Cell |volume=24 |issue=4 |pages=1560<U+2013>78 |pmid=22517318 |pmc=3398564}}</ref> Most of the polypeptides that lack N-terminal targeting sequences are the ones that are sent to the [[outer chloroplast membrane]], plus at least one sent to the [[inner chloroplast membrane]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

====Phosphorylation, chaperones, and transport====

After a chloroplast [[polypeptide]] is synthesized on a [[ribosome]] in the [[cytosol]], [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] energy can be used to [[phosphorylate]], or add a [[phosphate group]] to many (but not all) of them in their transit sequences.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> [[Serine]] and [[threonine]] (both very common in chloroplast transit sequences<U+2014>making up 20<U+2013>30% of the sequence)<ref name="JBC<U+2014>Transit sequence phosphorylation" /> are often the [[amino acids]] that accept the [[phosphate group]].<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>14-3-3 proteins">{{cite journal |doi=10.1105/tpc.12.1.53 |title=14-3-3 Proteins Form a Guidance Complex with Chloroplast Precursor Proteins in Plants |year=2000 |last1=May |first1=T. |journal=The Plant Cell Online |volume=12 |pages=53}}</ref><ref name="JBC<U+2014>Transit sequence phosphorylation" /> The [[protein kinase|enzyme]] that carries out the phosphorylation is [[enzyme specificity|specific]] for chloroplast polypeptides, and ignores ones meant for [[mitochondria]] or [[peroxisomes]].<ref name="JBC<U+2014>Transit sequence phosphorylation">{{cite journal |doi=10.1074/jbc.271.11.6545 |title=Phosphorylation of the Transit Sequence of Chloroplast Precursor Proteins |year=1996 |last1=Soll |first1=J r. |journal=Journal of Biological Chemistry |volume=271 |issue=11 |pages=6545<U+2013>54 |pmid=8626459 |last2=Soll |first2=J}}</ref>

Phosphorylation changes the polypeptide's shape,<ref name="JBC<U+2014>Transit sequence phosphorylation" /> making it easier for [[14-3-3 proteins]] to attach to the polypeptide.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" /> In plants, [[14-3-3 proteins]] only bind to chloroplast preproteins.<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>14-3-3 proteins" /> It is also bound by the [[heat shock protein|'''h'''eat '''s'''hock '''p'''rotein]] [[Hsp70]] that keeps the polypeptide from [[protein folding|folding]] prematurely.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> This is important because it prevents chloroplast proteins from assuming their active form and carrying out their chloroplast functions in the wrong place<U+2014>the [[cytosol]].<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>14-3-3 proteins" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc">{{cite journal |doi=10.1016/S0167-4889(01)00147-1 |title=Toc, Tic, and chloroplast protein import |year=2001 |last1=Jarvis |first1=Paul |last2=Soll |first2=J<U+00FC>rgen |journal=Biochimica et Biophysica Acta (BBA) - Molecular Cell Research |volume=1541 |pages=64<U+2013>79 |pmid=11750663 |issue=1<U+2013>2}}</ref> At the same time, they have to keep just enough shape so that they can be recognized and imported into the chloroplast.<ref name="The Plant Cell<U+2014>14-3-3 proteins" />

The heat shock protein and the 14-3-3 proteins together form a cytosolic guidance complex that makes it easier for the chloroplast polypeptide to get imported into the chloroplast.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Alternatively, if a chloroplast preprotein's transit peptide is not phosphorylated, a chloroplast preprotein can still attach to a heat shock protein or [[Toc159]]. These complexes can bind to the [[TOC complex]] on the outer chloroplast membrane using [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] energy.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

====The translocon on the outer chloroplast membrane <span style="font-weight: 400; ">(TOC)</span>====

{{expand section|date=June 2013|Minor TOC proteins, ''Arabidopsis'' mutants}}

The [[TOC complex]], or ''[[translocon|'''t'''ranslocon]] on the '''o'''uter '''c'''hloroplast membrane'', is a collection of proteins that imports preproteins across the [[outer chloroplast envelope]]. Five [[protein subunit|subunits]] of the TOC complex have been identified<U+2014>two [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]]-binding proteins [[Toc34]] and [[Toc159]], the protein import tunnel [[Toc75]], plus the proteins [[Toc64]]<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> and [[Toc12]].<ref name="Structure and Function of Plastids<U+2014>Protein import" />

The first three proteins form a core complex that consists of one Toc159, four to five Toc34s, and four Toc75s that form four holes in a disk 13 [[nanometers]] across. The whole core complex weighs about 500 [[kilodaltons]]. The other two proteins, Toc64 and Toc12, are associated with the core complex but are not part of it.<ref name="Structure and Function of Plastids<U+2014>Protein import" />

=====Toc34 and 33=====

{{plain image|File:TOC34.png|Toc34 from a [[pea plant]]. Toc34 has three almost identical molecules (shown in slightly different shades of green), each of which forms a [[Protein dimer|dimer]] with one of its adjacent molecules. Part of a [[Guanosine diphosphate|GDP]] molecule binding site is highlighted in pink.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Toc34">{{cite journal |doi=10.1038/nsb744 |title=Crystal structure of pea Toc34, a novel GTPase of the chloroplast protein translocon |year=2001 |last1=Sun |first1=Yuh-Ju |last2=Forouhar |first2=Farhad |last3=Li Hm |first3=Hsou-min |last4=Tu |first4=Shuh-Long |last5=Yeh |first5=Yi-Hong |last6=Kao |first6=Sen |last7=Shr |first7=Hui-Lin |last8=Chou |first8=Chia-Cheng |last9=Chen |first9=Chinpan |last10=Hsiao |first10=Chwan-Deng |journal=Nature Structural Biology |volume=9 |issue=2 |pages=95<U+2013>100 |pmid=11753431}}</ref>|350px|right|bottom|triangle|#58e11c}}

[[Toc34]] is an [[integral protein]] in the outer chloroplast membrane that's anchored into it by its [[hydrophobic]]<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Toc 159 A domain" /> [[C-terminal]] tail.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" /> Most of the protein, however, including its large [[guanosine triphosphate]] (GTP)-binding [[protein domain|domain]] projects out into the stroma.<ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" />

Toc34's job is to catch some chloroplast [[preproteins]] in the [[cytosol]] and hand them off to the rest of the TOC complex.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> When [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]], an energy molecule similar to [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] attaches to Toc34, the protein becomes much more able to bind to many chloroplast preproteins in the [[cytosol]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> The chloroplast preprotein's presence causes Toc34 to break GTP into [[guanosine diphosphate]] (GDP) and [[inorganic phosphate]]. This loss of GTP makes the Toc34 protein release the chloroplast preprotein, handing it off to the next TOC protein.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> Toc34 then releases the depleted GDP molecule, probably with the help of an unknown [[GDP exchange factor]]. A [[protein domain|domain]] of [[Toc159]] might be the exchange factor that carry out the GDP removal. The Toc34 protein can then take up another molecule of GTP and begin the cycle again.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Toc34 can be turned off through [[phosphorylation]]. A [[protein kinase]] drifting around on the outer chloroplast membrane can use [[Adenosine triphosphate|ATP]] to add a [[phosphate group]] to the Toc34 protein, preventing it from being able to receive another [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] molecule, inhibiting the protein's activity. This might provide a way to regulate protein import into chloroplasts.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" />

''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'' has two [[homology (chemistry)|homologous]] proteins, [[AtToc33]] and [[AtToc34]] (The ''At'' stands for '''''A'''rabidopsis '''t'''haliana''),<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" /> which are each about 60% identical in [[amino acid sequence]] to Toc34 in [[peas]] (called ''ps''Toc34).<ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" /> AtToc33 is the most common in ''Arabidopsis'',<ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" /> and it's the functional [[analogy (biology)|analogue]] of Toc34 because it can be turned off by phosphorylation. AtToc34 on the other hand cannot be phosphorylated.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="BBA<U+2014>Tic-toc" />

=====Toc159=====

[[Toc159]] is another [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] binding TOC [[protein subunit|subunit]], like [[Toc34]]. Toc159 has three [[protein domain|domains]]. At the [[N-terminal]] end is the A-domain, which is rich in [[acidic amino acids]] and takes up about half the protein length.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Toc 159 A domain">{{cite journal |doi=10.1104/pp.110.158048 |title=The Acidic A-Domain of Arabidopsis Toc159 Occurs as a Hyperphosphorylated Protein |year=2010 |last1=Agne |first1=B. |last2=Andr<U+00E8>s |first2=C. |last3=Montandon |first3=C. |last4=Christ |first4=B. |last5=Ertan |first5=A. |last6=Jung |first6=F. |last7=Infanger |first7=S. |last8=Bischof |first8=S. |last9=Baginsky |first9=S. |last10=Kessler |first10=F. |journal=Plant Physiology |volume=153 |issue=3 |pages=1016<U+2013>30 |pmid=20457805 |pmc=2899928}}</ref> The A-domain is often [[protein cleavage|cleaved]] off, leaving an 86 [[kilodalton]] fragment called [[Toc86]].<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Toc 159 A domain" /> In the middle is its [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]] binding domain, which is very similar to the [[homology (biology)|homologous]] GTP-binding domain in Toc34.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /><ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Toc 159 A domain" /> At the [[C-terminal]] end is the [[hydrophilic]] M-domain,<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> which anchors the protein to the outer chloroplast membrane.<ref name="Plant Physiology<U+2014>Toc 159 A domain" />

Toc159 probably works a lot like Toc34, recognizing proteins in the cytosol using [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]]. It can be regulated through [[phosphorylation]], but by a different [[protein kinase]] than the one that phosphorylates Toc34.<ref name="Structure and Function of Plastids<U+2014>Protein import" /> Its M-domain forms part of the tunnel that chloroplast preproteins travel through, and seems to provide the force that pushes preproteins through, using the energy from [[Guanosine triphosphate|GTP]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Toc159 is not always found as part of the TOC complex<U+2014>it has also been found dissolved in the [[cytosol]]. This suggests that it might act as a shuttle that finds chloroplast preproteins in the cytosol and carries them back to the TOC complex. There isn't a lot of direct evidence for this behavior though.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

A family of Toc159 proteins, [[Toc159]], [[Toc132]], [[Toc120]], and [[Toc90]] have been found in ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]''. They vary in the length of their A-domains, which is completely gone in Toc90. Toc132, Toc120, and Toc90 seem to have specialized functions in importing stuff like nonphotosynthetic preproteins, and can't replace Toc159.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

=====Toc75=====

{{plain image|File:Sucrose porin 1a0s.png|'''<U+03B2>-barrel''' The general shape of a <U+03B2>-barrel is a hollow cylinder lined by multiple [[<U+03B2>-sheets]]. Note that the protein depicted is ''not'' Toc75 specifically.|300px|right|top|triangle|#dfc400}}

[[Toc75]] is the most abundant protein on the outer chloroplast envelope. It's a [[transmembrane]] tube that forms most of the TOC pore itself. Toc75 is a [[<U+03B2>-barrel]] channel lined by 16 [[<U+03B2>-pleated sheets]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> The hole it forms is about 2.5 [[nanometers]] wide at the ends, and shrinks to about 1.4<U+2013>1.6 nanometers in diameter at its narrowest point<U+2014>wide enough to allow partially folded chloroplast preproteins to pass through.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Toc75 can also bind to chloroplast preproteins, but is a lot worse at this than Toc34 or Toc159.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'' has multiple [[isoforms]] of [[Toc75]] that are named by the [[chromosomal]] positions of the [[genes]] that code for them. [[AtToc75 III]] is the most abundant of these.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

====The translocon on the inner chloroplast membrane <span style="font-weight: 400; ">(TIC)</span>====
{{expand section|date=June 2013}}

The [[TIC translocon]], or '''''t'''ranslocon on the '''i'''nner '''c'''hloroplast membrane [[translocon]]''<!--Yes, that's what the source says--><ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> is another protein complex that imports proteins across the [[inner chloroplast envelope]]. Chloroplast polypeptide chains probably often travel through the two complexes at the same time, but the TIC complex can also retrieve preproteins lost in the [[chloroplast intermembrane space|intermembrane space]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" />

Like the [[Toc translocon|TOC translocon]], the TIC translocon has a large core [[Protein complex|complex]] surrounded by some loosely associated peripheral proteins like [[Tic110]], [[Tic40]], and [[Tic21]].<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC">{{cite journal |doi=10.1126/science.1229262 |title=Uncovering the Protein Translocon at the Chloroplast Inner Envelope Membrane |year=2013 |last1=Kikuchi |first1=Shingo |last2=B<U+00E9>dard |first2=Jocelyn |last3=Hirano |first3=Minako |last4=Hirabayashi |first4=Yoshino |last5=Oishi |first5=Maya |last6=Imai |first6=Midori |last7=Takase |first7=Mai |last8=Ide |first8=Toru |last9=Nakai |first9=Masato |journal=Science |volume=339 |issue=6119 |pages=571<U+2013>4 |pmid=23372012|bibcode = 2013Sci...339..571K }}</ref>
The core complex weighs about one million [[dalton (unit)|dalton]]s and contains [[Tic214]], [[Tic100]], [[Tic56]], and [[Tic20 I]], possibly three of each.<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

=====Tic20=====

[[Tic20]] is an [[Integral membrane protein|integral]] protein thought to have four [[Transmembrane domain|transmembrane]] [[<U+03B1>-helices]].<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> It's found in the 1 million [[Dalton (unit)|dalton]] TIC complex.<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" /> Because it's similar to [[Bacterial protein|bacterial]] [[amino acid]] transporters and the [[mitochondrial]] import protein [[Tim17]]<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> (''[[Translocase of the inner membrane|'''t'''ranslocase]] on the [[Inner mitochondrial membrane|'''i'''nner '''m'''itochondrial '''m'''embrane]]''),<ref>{{Cite book|isbn = 9783540214892|title = Mitochondrial Function and Biogenesis|url = http://books.google.com/books?id=ie5ZmOYHpVEC&pg=PA59|publisher = Springer|page = 59|year = 2004|author = Sean P Curran and Carla M Koehler}}</ref> it's been proposed to be part of the TIC import channel.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> There is no ''[[in vitro]]'' evidence for this though.<ref name="Nature<U+2014>Protein import" /> In ''[[Arabidopsis thaliana]]'', it is known that for about every five [[Toc75]] proteins in the outer chloroplast membrane, there are two [[Tic20 I]] proteins (the main [[Isoform|form]] of Tic20 in [[Arabidopsis thaliana|''Arabidopsis'']]) in the inner chloroplast membrane.<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

Unlike [[Tic214]], [[Tic100]], or [[Tic56]], Tic20 has [[homology (biology)|homologous]] relatives in [[cyanobacteria]] and nearly all chloroplast lineages, suggesting it evolved before the first chloroplast endosymbiosis. [[Tic214]], [[Tic100]], and [[Tic56]] are unique to [[chloroplastidan]] chloroplasts, suggesting that they evolved later.<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

=====Tic214=====
[[Tic214]] is another TIC core complex protein, named because it weighs just under 214 [[kilodaltons]]. It's 1786 [[amino acids]] long and is thought to have six [[transmembrane domains]] on its [[N-terminal]] end. Tic214 is notable for being coded for by [[chloroplast DNA]], more specifically the first [[open reading frame]] ''[[ycf1]]''. Tic214 and [[Tic20]] together probably make up the part of the one million [[Dalton (unit)|dalton]] TIC complex that spans the [[Transmembrane protein|entire membrane]]. Tic20 is buried inside the complex while Tic214 is exposed on both sides of the [[inner chloroplast membrane]].<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

=====Tic100=====
[[Tic100]] is a [[nuclear genome|nuclear encoded]] protein that's 871 [[amino acids]] long. The 871 amino acids collectively weigh slightly less than 100 thousand [[dalton (unit)|daltons]], and since the mature protein probably doesn't lose any amino acids when itself imported into the chloroplast (it has no [[cleavable transit peptide]]), it was named Tic100. Tic100 is found at the edges of the 1 million dalton complex on the side that faces the [[chloroplast intermembrane space]].<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

=====Tic56=====
[[Tic56]] is also a [[nuclear genome|nuclear encoded]] protein. The [[preprotein]] its gene encodes is 527 amino acids long, weighing close to 62 thousand [[dalton (unit)|daltons]]; the mature form probably undergoes processing that trims it down to something that weighs 56 thousand daltons when it gets imported into the chloroplast. Tic56 is largely embedded inside the 1 million dalton complex.<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

Tic56 and [[Tic100]] are highly [[gene conservation|conserved]] among land plants, but they don't resemble any protein whose function is known. Neither has any [[transmembrane domains]].<ref name="Science<U+2014>TIC" />

{{clear}}
 <!--

<div style="float: right; clear: right; width: 30%; background: #73d9ff; height: 30px; text-align: center; line-height: 30px; color: white;">'''Epiplastid membrane'''</div>

<div style="float: right; clear: right; margin-top: 100px; width: 20%; background: #0dc0b2; height: 30px; text-align: center; line-height: 30px; color: white;">'''Periplastid membrane'''</div>

<div style="float: right; clear: right; margin-top: 100px; width: 40%; background: #0dc04f; height: 30px; text-align: center; line-height: 30px; color: white;">'''Outer chloroplast membrane'''</div>

<div style="float: right; clear: right; margin-top: 100px; width: 40%; background: #0dc04f; height: 30px; text-align: center; line-height: 30px; color: white;">'''Inner chloroplast membrane'''</div>

